n in state bonds in South Da\nkota. but this central credit agency\nis to be so established that this cap\nital so furnished is to be managed,\nnot by authorities answerable to the\npeople, Aiut by gamblers answerable\n'o ore another.\n^1*8\nCLAIRE CITY, SOUTH DAKOTA, JANUARY 28, 1921\nThe ruin which is overtaking\nbusiness is for lack of a market.\nThe lack of a market for any one\narticle is because of the inability\nof someone to sell some other art\nicle. Those who are to be consumers\nought lirst to be, producers. Those\nwho are to be buyers must first be\nsellers. The denial of credit is\nstrangling the market. The denial\nof credit has set prices tumbling.\nIt has brought foreclosures attach\nments are enforced sales in a broken\nmarket. The resources and powers\nof no state are sullicient to deal ef\nfectively with this situation.\nThe trouble is that the markets\nare national. The Constitution of\nthe United States gives to the Na\ntional Government, a practical mon\nopoly in financial affairs. Congress\nalone can act effectively, and the\ngamblers who have promoted this\ndenial of credit and are proceeding\nwith plans to appropriate the pledg\ned collaterals of a nation, are in\ncontrol of Congress.\nH'Wi\nThe wheels could be started im\nmediately. Unemployment could be\nmade an end of. The condition of\nindustrial paralysis and of commer\ncial stagnation could be ended at\nonce, by excluding all gamblers from\nthe market, by forbidding anyone\nto buy what he does not use making\nit a felony to grant credit for gam\nbling purposes ruling the specula\ntor out of the market: granting the\nneeded credits to the real producers:\ngiving them a chance to exchange\ntheir products with one another\nby restoring credits restore prices\nthe producers.\nWill Congress do it? Either this\nCongress or the Congress recently\nelected will do it or another elec\ntion will create a Congress that will\nrepresent the useful people and not\nthe gamblers.\nSMB\nand bv restoring prices make the employed from interests outside the\nsale of products possible on a basis state, to take these industrial laws\nwhich would not mean the ruin of I into the courts on the ground of\na Final Sliow-down\nThe last week has seen a most\nremarkable occurrence. Six months\nago the newspaper organs of tha\nexploiters and their political agents\nCarl J. Rice\nSons\n8!\u00ab\nMet. Bnk. lildg.,\napolis, Minn.\nMinne-\nA Good Duplex (house for\ntwo families) in perfect re\npair in a good district in\nSou tli Minneapolis bringing\n$50.00 per month rental at\nthe bargain pricet of $3800.00.\nThis brings you over 15 per\noent on your investment.\nOther properties at equally\nood bargains.\nWe have a number of good\nmortgages Minneapolis\nproperty as well as on good\nfarms at 8 per cent interest.\nFarms bought and sold in\n\u2022Roberts county and elsewhere.\nCARL J. RICE SONS\nFormerly of Peever, 8. D.\nWm.\nSwedlund\nAll Kinds of\nReal Estate\nInsurance\nBonds\n1\n-R'-'K\nSystem that the lime had come to\ndellate. Just why deflation was nec\nessary was not explained, but the\nspokesmen of the plunderbund an\nnounced that the time was up. Cred\nits were everywhere withdrawn and\nthis was especially true of the small\ner batiks and the farmers. None of\nthese were represented in the inner\ncircle of the organized grafters who\ncontrol the organized credits of\nAmerica, if not of all the earth.\nri\nhe attack\n011\nof the whole country was made es\npecially severe and uncompromising\nin the state of North Dakota. When\nNorth Dakota established its own\nstate owned bank and pledged the\nstate credits to the creation and\nmaintenance of certain state owned\nindustries, the word was sent out\nthat these enterprises could not be\nfinanced. The usual bond buyers\nsent their representatives in great\nnumbers to North Dakota, asking\nfor exclusive options in the handling\nof the bonds. It was suspected that\npossibly there was the sinister pur\npose in this, of getting control of\nthe sale and then preventing the\nsale. Exclusive option was not\ngiven, but the sale was held up just\nas effectively by another process.\nI Action was commenced in the courts,\norganized, financed and attorneys\ntheir unconstitutionality, and then to\nproclaim to bond buyers everywhere\nthat it would be unsafe to invest\nin bonds held up by litigation.\nThe United States Court, how\never, decided that the enterprises\nwere constitutional and that the\nbonds were in proper form that\nthere was no legal reason why they\nshould not be marketed.\nDut the bond buying agencies\nhad entered a boycott, and the effort,\nto sell thru the usual agencies was\nwithout avail. Activities were lim\nited, construction work suspended\nand the proclamation made that\npublic ownership was a failure.\nFollowing this, the most vicious\ncampaign within any American state,\norganized and financed by great pri\nvate interests outside the state,\nmade an effort to capture the au\nthorities of the state by the pollu\ntion of its ballot box.\nThe Nonpartisan League of farm\ners and the trade unions retained\ncontrol of the upper house, of most\nof the state offices, of all the author\nities concerned in the industrial\nprogram, and lost by only a few\nvotes in the lower house.\nThe enterprise which had been\nespecially blocked by these tactics\nconsisted of an effort to finance home\nbuilders, that those who cared to\nown homes and farms of their own\nmight be financed in their undertak\nings. without being victimized by\nland gamblers and mortgage sharks.\nIt was an effort to furninsh farm\ncredits at cost and to extend credits\non warehouse certificates in the\nmarketing of the annual harvests\nand finally, by entering the field of\nwarehousing the harvest and of mil\nling at least some portion of it, to\nbreak the power of the grain gamb\nlers.\nand spokesmen 011 the platform were tablish themselves as the absolute\nproclaiming that the only way to masters of international credit,\ninsure prosperity and lower the cost They were able to do this thru ad\nof living was by increased produc- vancmg the cost of living and ap\ntion. Increased production was the propriating the plunder so taken\nresult. from American consumers as profits,\n1 and then by converting these profits\nThree months ago the word was '\"to the v.r.r debts of practically\nsent out thru the Federal Reserve all of the nations.\nr,:o'i-\nProceeding in the same efTort In\nother states, and waging war at all\ntimes more viciously in North Dako\nta, credits were denied farmers on\nany terms, with millions of values\nready for the market, credits were\nviciously and continuously refused.\nMortgage foreclosures threatened,\nsheriff's eales used as arguments,\nthe smaller banks pushed to the\nwall, and with ample assets compel\nled to close their doors.\nNow the legislature is in session\nand the representatives of the in\nternational Wall Street Syndicate\nhave come to North Dakota with an\nultimatum. This is the group of\nmen who took advantage of the\nworst, disaster that has ever befallen\nthe race of men to gather together\nin this country more than one-half\nof all the gold on earth and to es-\nThls Wall Street ultimatum is\nthat the state shall enter into an\nagreement to limit, its activities in\npublicly owned enerprises to the\namount of seven million dollars.and\nwill agree to revise the industrial\nlegislation under direction of the\nattorneys of the bond selling gamb\nlers, then the seven million dollars\nwill be forthcoming and North Da\nkota will be permitted to play its\nII\nestablished credits\nIN\nof\nThere's More Real Satisfaction\"\nsays the Good Judge\nthe ten Middle Western States served\nby the Standard Oil Company (Indiana)\nthere is one automobile for each 9\npersons. It is estimated that 65% of these\nvehicles are owned by farmers. That is the\nutmost of efficiency in refining, manufac\nturing, and distributing gasoline and other\npetrcleum products is needed most in this\ngreat territory.\nTo indicate the tremendous increase in the num\nber of cars and trucks, the following statement\n1919 and 1920 registrations by states is given:\nSTATES\n1919\nSo. Dakota\nIowa\nMinnesota\nMissouri\nKansas\nNo. Dakota\nMichigan\nWisconsin\nIndiana\nIllinois\nNumber 24\nlittle game within these narrow lim\nits,\u2014less than the needs of a single\ncounty, leaving the rest\nof North\nDakota and the rest of the world\nto\nthe free hand of the plunderbund.\nThe slate of North Dakota has re\nfused to sell its soul for seven mil\nlion dollars worth of \"pottage,\" or\nto betray the useful workers of\nAmerica. This treasonable, arro\ngant, unendurable insult to the state\nof North Dakota carries with it the\nmost serious reflection upon the\ncharacter of every other state in the\nUnion. One cannot avoid the infer\nence that North Dakota alone has\nbeen sent this demand for a complete\nsurrender to Wall Street and its at\ntorneys for the reason that all tho\nothers have already done so.\nIn a little of the Real To\nbacco Ghc-w, than you ever 1\ngot out cf the ordinary kind.\nThe good rich taste lasts so\nlong you don't need a fresh\nchew nearly as often\u2014that's\nwhy it costs you less to chew I#\nthis class of tobacco.\nAny man who uses the Real\nTobacco Chew will tell you\nthat.\nPut ufl in two styles\nW-B CUT is a long fine-cut tobacco\nRIGHT CUT is a short-cut tobacco\nW a a 1 1 0 7 a a N O\nWhere\nOil Efficiency\nIs\n1920\n104,625\n363,000\n259,743\n229,577\n228,601\n82,885\n296,378\n236,974\n277,255\n478,438\n2,557,476\n122,040\n442,200\n323,572\n295,817\n265,385\n90,840\n412,275\n303,246\n332,207\n_569,127\n3,156,709\nTo enable these machines to operate in all\nweather, under all conditions, and wherever they\nmay be located, an adequate supply of gasoline is\nneeded. To supply this need is the constant\nendeavor of the Standard Oil Company (Indiana).\nThe refineries operated by this Company are\nworking night and day to increase the yield of\ngasoline taken from crude oil. without in any\nway sacrificing the quality of the gasoline.\nThe Standard Oil Company (Indiana) operates\ndistribution system maintained at as near to\n100% efficiency as is humanly possible. To do this\ncalls for a minute and unwearying study of local\nconditions, and for constant anticipation of\nfuture needs.\nAll activities of the Standard Oil Company\n(Indiana) are co-ordinated to the highest degree\nof efficiency to insure maximum economy.\nThus in the Middle West, where efficiency is\nneeded most, the Standard Oil Company (Indiana)\nis performing this essential economic service to\nthe benefit of all the people.\nStandard Oil Company\n(In#\u2014)\n910 So. Michigan Ave., Chicago\na\n2375","height":"27620","width":"19436"}}
